Author::::mypipsranout
DateTime::::2016-02-27T03:57:37Z
I'd have to read the original reports and articles on these sites you mention, to judge them, but most peer reviewed theories claiming evidence of early meat consumption are processualist, fail to acknowledge their own bias' and are guilty of 'presenting the past'. I've read many that have been widely reported as fact in the mainstream media and yet have been heavily criticized by peers. Reading material evidence is always subjective, but as better scientific analysis is developed you can get a better picture (though, still a subjective one, everything has to be read and interpreted by someone), and most isotope analysis of early humans show evidence of plant based diets. In Europe, even as late as the neolithic, there is very little isotope evidence for widespread meat consumption, until it's conspicuous consumption for a short period of c.50yrs coinciding with the collapse of that society and the beginning of the bronze age. Otzi is a good example of how isotope analysis has turned earlier assumptions on their heads, he was found with a belly full of meat, so it was thought meat formed a regular part of his diet, the isotope analysis showed it didn't and he ate a mainly plant based diet, his belly was full of a meal eaten in unusual circumstances. My point being that even if at times in the past people needed to eat meat occasionally, that is not the case for the majority of humans alive on the planet today. In fact the no.1 cause of world hunger is animal agriculture, so doing so actively causes global food insecurity.



